Fix a bug and add an enhancement
Let's practice what we learned by simulating project requirements. We have a bug to fix and add an enhancement to our drink order web app.
Hey Slacker!
Remember, we're here to help.
Join the KCWiT #codingandcocktails Slack Channel: kcwit.slack.com

Fix a bug by using equality and conditional logic
You're getting ready to release the web page to your customer, Coding & Cocktails, and realize there's a bug! You can submit an order without a name. And if you submit an order without selecting a drink order, we see an error in the console. Let's check to make sure a name and a drink order exists before submitting the order.

Open Atom and start atom-live-server. Open Chrome DevTools in the browser tab that atom-live-server opens.
Don't forget to save your file after each code change to see your web page reload. If another browser opens, you can open Chrome and open a tab using the same URL as the other browser tab.


In my-script.js, inside the first click event handler, wrap the call to submitOrder in an if statement. Add an equality check for orderName variable is not empty in the if condition.


Need a little help? Expand this section for guidance. 

Your code will look like this


if (orderName) {
       submitOrder(orderName, drinkId);
}




Remember, in JavaScript, null, undefined, and empty strings are falsy.


Try submitting an order without the name. A drink order didn't submit. Yay! Now try submitting an order where the order contains only whitespace by using the spacebar to add one space in the order name. Uh oh.

We can use the built in trim() function to trim leading and trailing whitespace from user entry. The trim() function returns a new string without leading and trailing whitespace. We can add the call to trim() right after retrieving the value of the input element.Your code will look like this
const orderName = document.getElementById('order-form-input').value.trim();


Try submitting an order with spaces as the name. A drink order didn't submit. Yay! We're getting closer! Now try submitting an order without the drink selected. Uh oh. We still see an error in the console: Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read property 'id' of null.
Look at the code to query for the radio button. We use document.querySelector('input[type="radio"]:checked').id. But if we don't select a drink, the querySelector can't find any elements matching a checked radio button. The return from querySelector() where no elements match the criteria is null. We then try to get the id property of null. We need to check the element is not null before proceeding.


Change the variable name drinkId to drinkElement and remove the call to get the id property.


Need a little help? Expand this section for guidance. 

Your code will look like this


const drinkElement = document.querySelector('input[type="radio"]:checked');





We can now check if drinkElement is null. We can do this at the same time as the if (orderName) expression. We will use logical operators. We want both orderName and drinkElement to be truthy before calling submitOrder. We can use the logical AND operator: &&. Your if expression will look like this
if (orderName && drinkElement)


Update the call to submitOrder to send the id of the drinkElement so that the submitOrder function still works.


Need a little help? Expand this section for guidance. 

Your code will look like this


submitOrder(orderName, drinkElement.id);





Try submitting a drink order without selecting a drink. Yay! A drink order was not submitted!


Enhance the web app by adding a way to show a limited drink menu
Our bartender, Laura, doesn't want to have so many drinks available each session. She wants the ability to limit the drink menu to only show drinks she's prepared that evening. We will add a new property to the drink object and filter the array when building out the menu.
Here is another example where building out the menu programmatically allows us to easily add more functionality.

In my-script.js, in the drinkArray, add a new property to each drink object called isAvailable. The value is a boolean so set the values to true or false.


Need a little help? Expand this section for guidance. 

Your drink object inside the array will look like this


{
      'id': 'focusedLady',
      'label': 'Focused Lady',
      'photoId': 'eXdKs9d37Sc',
      'isAvailable': true
}


Don't forget the single quotes and a comma between the photoId property and the new property. Make sure you add the property to every object!



In the buildDrinkMenu method we want to create a new array of drinks where isAvailable == true and use that array to build the menu. We can do that using the built in filter() method on arrays. After the fragment variable declaration, but be before the forEach, create a new variable called availableDrinks and type the following code
const availableDrinks = this.drinkArray.filter( (arrayElement) => {
   return arrayElement.isAvailable === true;
});

Let's walk through what we did here. We created a variable called availableDrinks. We access the drinkArray buy using this and iterate over each drink in drinkArray to apply the filter conditional. If arrayElement.isAvailable == true, that drink is added to availableDrinks array.


Update the code to build the drink menu using the drinks in availableDrinks.


Need a little help? Expand this section for guidance. 

Your code will look like this


const availableDrinks = this.drinkArray.filter( (element) => {
      return element.isAvailable == true;
});

availableDrinks.forEach( (drink) => {
      ...
});





Does the drink menu show a subset of the drink array? Great job!!




Way to stick with it!!



Checkpoint 
Compare your my-script.js against the answer key for your work so far. It might look a little different depending on spacing and photos you selected.  










                Expand this section to compare your work.



             You can also compare your my-script.js file with our answer key if the image is too difficult to read.
